## (1)(b) OLSR Protocol

> Describe and give the diagram of the IETF OLSR (Optimised Link State Routing) protocol used in MANETs. Discuss a deficiency of this protocol. *(10 marks)*

---

**OLSR** is a **proactive** routing protocol for MANETs. It maintains routes to all destinations **continuously**, even before they're needed.

**Key Concept: MPR (Multipoint Relay)**

Instead of flooding, only selected **MPR nodes** forward messages. This dramatically reduces overhead.

::mpr-selection

---

**How OLSR Works:**

1. **HELLO messages** - nodes discover neighbors and select MPRs
2. **TC (Topology Control) messages** - MPRs broadcast link state info
3. **Route calculation** - each node builds routing table from TC messages

::flooding-comparison

---

**Deficiency of OLSR:**

- **High overhead in sparse networks** - proactive updates waste bandwidth when few routes are needed
- **Slow convergence** - TC messages have periodic intervals, so route changes aren't instant
- **Memory intensive** - every node stores routes to ALL destinations
- **Not scalable** - overhead grows with network size

> OLSR is best for **dense, stable networks** where routes are frequently used. For sparse or highly mobile networks, reactive protocols like AODV are better.

