## (1)(c) WiMAX Scheduling

> Describe the main scheduling proposals for WiMAX, by differentiating between channel-aware and channel-unaware schedulers. Draw the schedulers using detailed flow diagrams. *(8 marks)*

---

**Channel-Unaware Schedulers:**

Don't consider current channel conditions. Simple but inefficient.

**1. Round Robin (RR)**

::round-robin

- Serves each user in turn, equal time slots
- **Pro:** Fair, simple
- **Con:** Ignores channel quality, wastes slots on users with bad channels

**2. Weighted Fair Queuing (WFQ)**

- Like RR but weighted by subscription/priority
- Higher-paying users get more slots

---

**Channel-Aware Schedulers:**

Consider real-time channel conditions. More efficient but complex.

**1. Max C/I (Maximum Carrier-to-Interference)**

::max-ci

- Always serves user with **best channel**
- **Pro:** Maximum throughput
- **Con:** Starves users with poor channels (unfair)

**2. Proportional Fair (PF)**

- Balances throughput and fairness
- Serves user with best **relative** channel (current / average)
- **Pro:** Good throughput AND fairness
- **Con:** More complex to implement

---

**Comparison:**

| Scheduler | Aware? | Throughput | Fairness |
|-----------|--------|------------|----------|
| Round Robin | No | Low | High |
| WFQ | No | Low | Weighted |
| Max C/I | Yes | Highest | Lowest |
| Proportional Fair | Yes | High | Good |
